reprogrammed by a single note, fans attending the band's concerts at the Rose 
Bowl tonight and Sunday need not be in a hurry to get there on time. Show up 
half an hour late and you'll still catch everything that's worth hearing and 
seeing. 
</P>
<P>
 Among the things latecomers will miss is an unforgivably limp show-opening 
rendition of the 1967-vintage space-rocker "Astronomy Domine." Subsequent songs 
from "A Momentary Lapse of Reason," the 1987 comeback album Pink Floyd released 
after its acrimonious split with lyricist and conceptualist Roger Waters, and 
the newly released "The Division Bell" were like the Queen Mary -- stately as 
you could wish, but going nowhere fast. During the first five songs of the set, 
