<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH COAST LEAGUE BASEBALL ROUNDUP; MATER DEI'S HARRIS TOSSES NO-HITTER, BEATS 
SAN CLEMENTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JASON H. REID, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Adam Harris last experienced this feeling at 9, but candy and cartoons 
dominated his thoughts as much as baseball back then. 
</P>
<P>
 So when the Mater Dei senior right-hander clenched the ball in his glove and 
stepped on first base for the final out, he fully appreciated the 
accomplishment this time. 
</P>
<P>
 Harris pitched a no-hitter Friday in the first-place Monarchs' 11-0 rout of 
host San Clemente in a South Coast League game, enabling Mater Dei to sweep the 
season series. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's been awhile for me," Harris said. "All this year I've taken no-hitters 
into the third and fourth (innings), so it felt really good to finally get 
one."  
</P>
<P>
 The no-hitter is the first of the season for Mater Dei (11-5-1, 6-1 in 
league), which is alone atop the league standings and ranked fifth in the 
county. 
</P>
<P>
 Only a first-inning walk to Robert Frith denied Harris (5-0) a prefect game. 
Still, though, Harris faced the minimum of 21 batters because Monarch catcher 
Matt Treanor nailed Frith at second on a steal attempt. Harris, who entered the 
game with the county's No. 2 earned-run average, lowered his ERA to 0.41. 
</P>
<P>
 Harris ended the game by receiving a soft toss from first baseman Tim Wetzel, 
who fielded Frith's ground ball to his right. Harris struck out four. 
</P>
<P>
 "All my pitches were on; fastball, curveball, slider," Harris said. "But I 
just want to say thanks to (shortstop) Erik (Mattern) because he saved it for 
me." 
</P>
<P>
 Mattern made a spectacular defensive play in the fifth inning to rob Mike Wood 
of a hit. He ran nearly to the lip of the outfield grass, jumped high to field 
the ball on a hop, did a 180-degree spin and fired a perfect throw to first 
that just got Wood for the third out. 
</P>
<P>
 "I didn't even know he was throwing (a no-hitter)," Mattern said. "I got back 
to the dugout and everyone was patting me on the back and congratulating me. 
That's when I knew." 
</P>
<P>
 Said Monarch Coach Bob Ickes: "It was the play of the game." 
</P>
<P>
 Mercifully, San Clemente is done with Mater Dei -- at least for the regular 
season. 
</P>
<P>
 The Tritons (11-6, 4-3) were routed by the Monarchs on Wednesday, 21-8, and 
lost the season's first meeting, 6-0. 
</P>
<P>
 San Clemente entered the week in a three-way tie for first, but now finds 
itself in third and looking up at the Monarchs and Dana Hills (10-7-1, 5-2). 
</P>
<P>
 In other league games: 
</P>
<P>
 Dana Hills 13, El Toro 4 -- Tyson Loreque hit a grand slam in the top of the 
seventh for Dana Hills (10-7-1, 5-2). Catcher Scott Maynard went two for two 
with four runs batted in and Mark Richardson went four for five. 
</P>
<P>
 Seth Etherton pitched a complete game to improve to 6-0 on the season. 
Etherton gave up four hits, striking out five and walking two. 
</P>
<P>
 Capistrano Valley 5, Mission Viejo 1 -- Brandon Puffer hit a home run in the 
third for Capistrano Valley (12-5, 3-4). Peter Zamora (4-1) pitched a complete 
game, striking out nine and walking one. Brian Harnetiaux went two for two with 
a triple and an RBI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
